******
[2]
Date: Thu 15 Aug 2019
Source: Diario de Sevilla [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=https://www.diariodesevilla.es/sevilla/listeriosis-Empresa-retira-mechada-investiga-contaminacion_0_1382861952.html&prev=search


The Ministry of Health and Families has issued a health alert on Thursday [15 Aug 2018] and has withdrawn from the sale and consumption a meatloaf manufactured in Seville, with the commercial name La Mecha, which has caused an outbreak of listeriosis that has affected 40 people.

In the last 3 weeks, 40 cases of listeriosis have been recorded in the provinces of Seville and Malaga. Some of these people were hospitalized. As reported by the Ministry, the alert has been issued after verifying that this product, manufactured by the Magrudis firm, domiciled in Seville, is the causative agent of the listeriosis outbreak. The health alert, activated after the development of the protocols and the appropriate inspections, means the withdrawal of said product from the sale and consumption.

The company that manufactures this meat, which according to the Ministry has maintained a close collaboration with Public Health during the investigation, has already communicated these facts to its clients.

The meat company La Mecha reported on Thursday [15 Aug 2019] that it has found anomalies in some items: "After having detected anomalies in the preparation of some batches of our product, Mecha meat, La Mecha brand, we communicate that said product should not be consumed by our customers or final consumers."

Listeriosis is an infection caused by bacteria that may be present in uncooked meats. It causes fever and acute gastroenteritis, and is especially serious in cases of pregnant women, children and people with previous pathologies. The services of the Virgen del Rocio, Macarena and Juan Ramon Jimenez hospitals are attentive to the occurrence of possible cases of this disease.

