Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Huelva, with a population of 144 258 residents, is a city located along the Gulf of Cadiz coast in southwestern Spain in the autonomous community of Andalusia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huelva). Seville, with a metropolitan population of about 1.5 million, is the capital and largest city of the autonomous community of Andalusia, located about 80 km (50 mi) inland from the Gulf of Cadiz coast (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seville). A map showing the location of Huelva and Seville can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Seville,+Spain.

The 1st news report above does not specify the type of meat involved in the listeriosis outbreak in Seville and Huelva, Spain, although the 2nd news report above says that it is a "meatloaf". Elsewhere it has been characterized as "shredded meat" (https://www.diariodesevilla.es/sevilla/listeriosis-Empresa-retira-mechada-investiga-contaminacion_0_1382861952.html). Adequate cooking of the meat before eating should have markedly reduced the risk for listeriosis. However, refrigerated ready-to-eat cold cut meats are well-recognized sources for listeriosis. Even if initial contamination added only a few _Listeria_ organisms to the food, the contamination can be significant for refrigerated foods because _Listeria monocytogenes_ can subsequently multiply at refrigerator temperatures to sufficient number to cause disease. This type of meat product should not be served to people who are likely to be at increased risk for listeriosis, such as pregnant women, adults aged 65 years or older, and people with weakened immune systems.

The meat ("La Mecha" made by the company Magrudis, based in Seville) suspected to be the source has been recalled, but because it can take up to 70 days after exposure to _Listeria_ for symptoms of listeriosis to develop, more cases may be expected.

In the USA and Europe, clusters of related cases are identified based on clinical isolates of _L. monocytogenes_ that have similar genotypes. Food is confirmed to be the source if _Listeria_ isolated from it has a genotype that matches the genotype of the clinical outbreak strain. We await further developments in the investigation of this outbreak. - Mod.ML

